snippet.textDisplay:
As someone who makes a bunch of bone broth, mostly in the form of Pho. I prefer Beef tendon over chicken feet. As it not only adds everything the chicken feet do, but has the added bonus of being delicious. That said, Par boiling the bones, tendon or other meat products before roasting actually eliminates the metallic flavor you mention. This allows you to keep the goodness that comes out of the marrow without getting off flavors. As to how much bone broth do I make? Well my family eats a dish with it used on average 3 days a week. I used to use a huge 80 quart pot so I could store large amounts of it, until I figured how to do it faster in the instant pot. The magic number for me turns out to be high pressure for 2 hours and letting naturally depressure. This results in a clear broth that is perfectly gelatin at room temp every single time.


Also a stick of Ceylon Cinnamon included really brings it to a whole new level.
